`crates/ctx-context/` is the standalone `ctx-context` crate: a read-only context server that computes the rollup/intent/leaf `.ctx` chain above a repo path and either prints it (CLI) or injects the unseen portion as `additionalContext` in a Claude Code `PostToolUse` hook. Depending on this crate means depending on `cli::dispatch` and `hook::run` (under `src/`), both generic over the `Env` trait so no caller needs real filesystem/env access to exercise the logic.

The manifest (`Cargo.toml`) defines both a `src/main.rs` binary and a `src/lib.rs` library target from the same source tree; the two must stay in sync when either entry point's module wiring changes. `src/` holds the full implementation as a single pipeline (`repo_path` → `chain` → `serve` → `session`) shared by `cli.rs` and `hook.rs`; `tests/` is the only place that exercises that pipeline end-to-end, since no source file's unit tests cover the serve+hook+session interaction. A change to path-escape validation, chain ordering, or absent-scaffolding sentinels in `src/` must be mirrored in `tests/chain_serve.rs`; a change to session-cache location, keying, or fail-open behavior must be mirrored in `tests/hook_session.rs`. Both test files maintain independent `FakeEnv` fixtures rather than sharing one, so directory-detection semantics changed in `src/env.rs` need matching updates in both fakes or the suites can silently diverge.

Crate-wide invariant: all process/argv/stdin I/O and all `std::fs`/`std::env` access stays behind the `Env` trait and the binary shell (`main.rs`), never called directly from library modules — this is what makes the `tests/` fakes valid stand-ins and is enforced by the workspace's print-stdout lint restriction.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence check applies.